<article>
    <h1>Sci&#xAD;ence and vir&#xAD;tual re&#xAD;al&#xAD;ity help piece to&#xAD;gether what hap&#xAD;pened</h1>
    <h2>Trainees at Civil De&#xAD;fence Academy use vir&#xAD;tual re&#xAD;al&#xAD;ity soft&#xAD;ware with re&#xAD;al&#xAD;is&#xAD;tic sce&#xAD;nar&#xAD;ios</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201130/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-30"><time>2020-11-30</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Zai&#xAD;han Mo&#xAD;hamed Yu&#xAD;sof Se&#xAD;nior Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent zai&#xAD;han@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Some fire in­ves­ti­ga­tion cases can be straight­for­ward, but for large-scale fires or com­plex fires such as in­dus­trial fires, find­ing the ori­gin and cause of fire can be like find­ing a nee­dle in a haystack.</p>
    <p>When lives are lost in an in­dus­trial blaze or a home is gut­ted, the Fire In­ves­ti­ga­tion Unit (FIU) of the Sin­ga­pore Civil De­fence Force (SCDF) be­gins the un­en­vi­able task of piec­ing to­gether what hap­pened.</p>
    <p>The job be­comes harder when clues may not be ap­par­ent or have been de­stroyed by the fire.</p>
    <p>Since Fe­bru­ary, trainees at the Civil De­fence Academy (CDA) have started us­ing vir­tual re­al­ity soft­ware – called Vir­tual Re­al­ity Fire In­ves­ti­ga­tion (VRFI) – to sup­ple­ment and sharpen their in­ves­ti­ga­tion skills.</p>
    <p>But FIU’s se­nior fire in­ves­ti­ga­tor Cindy Han counts on her in­quis­i­tive na­ture and job ex­pe­ri­ence to help solve the puz­zles. Cap­tain Han, 34, told The Straits Times at a re­cent train­ing ses­sion: “You want to make sure that your in­ves­ti­ga­tion find­ings can give clo­sure to fam­i­lies (of vic­tims)... and pre­vent (such in­ci­dents) from hap­pen­ing again.”</p>
    <p>Lieu­tenant-Colonel (LTC) Dannies Ang, Com­man­der of FIU, said the unit works closely with other gov­ern­ment agen­cies – in­clud­ing other SCDF de­part­ments – on fire safety and pub­lic ed­u­ca­tion when­ever it de­tects fire trends through its anal­y­sis.</p>
    <p>LTC Ang, 39, said: “Fire in­ves­ti­ga­tion is a sci­ence based on an es­tab­lished in­ves­ti­ga­tion method­ol­ogy and foren­sic anal­y­sis, cou­pled with a touch of good old ‘Sher­lock Holmes’ de­duc­tive rea­son­ing.</p>
    <p>“Some fire in­ves­ti­ga­tion cases can be straight­for­ward, but for large-scale fires or com­plex fires such as in­dus­trial fires, find­ing the ori­gin and cause of fire can be like find­ing a nee­dle in a haystack.”</p>
    <p>LIEU­TENANT-COLONEL DANNIES ANG, Com­man­der of FIU</p>
    <p>Capt Han, who holds a mas­ter’s de­gree in foren­sics sci­ence and a grad­u­ate cer­tifi­cate in fire and ar­son in­ves­ti­ga­tion, ad­mits that un­like TV dra­mas where fire cases are solved within an hour, her in­ves­ti­ga­tions may take days or months.</p>
    <p>She has to con­sider the avail­abil­ity of closed-cir­cuit tele­vi­sion footage, as well as the trauma ex­pe­ri­enced by vic­tims be­fore wit­ness in­ter­views can be done.</p>
    <p>Capt Han, who joined SCDF in 2009, con­sid­ers the signs she sees at a post-fire scene as the most im­por­tant – they tell whether a fire was ac­ci­den­tal or the work of an ar­son­ist.</p>
    <p>Burn pat­terns and dam­age to home ap­pli­ances may in­di­cate the ori­gin and in­ten­sity of a fire. But pe­cu­liar fire dam­age may in­di­cate that ac­cel­er­ants were used, she said.</p>
    <p>To help in her pre­lim­i­nary hy­poth­e­sis, Capt Han may use a hy­dro­car­bon gas de­tec­tor or even a fire in­ves­ti­ga­tion dog, trained to dis­tin­guish be­tween seven types of flammable sub­stances.</p>
    <p>Some of the skills she has learnt are now be­ing taught in a class­room set­ting via the VRFI sys­tem.</p>
    <p>The in­struc­tor-led train­ing has six re­al­is­tic sce­nar­ios and teaches trainees the steps in fire in­ves­ti­ga­tion and the im­por­tance of scene preser­va­tion. A stu­dent puts on VR gog­gles and uses hand con­trols to se­lect items such as flood­lights and a cam­era, com­monly used by in­ves­ti­ga­tors at a post-fire scene.</p>
    <p>The VRFI sys­tem at CDA is por­ta­ble and can be taken to the fire sta­tions to train in­ves­ti­ga­tors there.</p>
    <p>In the real world, the burn pat­terns for fires sus­pected to in­volve per­sonal mo­bil­ity de­vices (PMDs) ap­pear ran­dom and spread out.</p>
    <p>Said Capt Han: “When you take a closer look, you may be able to see the ex­ploded bat­tery cells fall­ing in other places.</p>
    <p>“This will ex­plain why, even when the burnt cells are far from the PMD, these ar­eas catch fire.”</p>
    <p>FIU’s con­tri­bu­tion to the ex­panded in­ter-agency Ac­tive Mo­bil­ity Fire Safety task force – which was set up to raise aware­ness of PMD fires and to pro­mote the safe use of these de­vices – may have re­sulted in fewer PMD fires. The task force com­prises the Land Trans­port Au­thor­ity, Hous­ing Board, SCDF and En­ter­prise Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>In the first half of last year, there were 50 cases of PMD fires com­pared with 26 cases in the same pe­riod this year.</p>
    <p>FIU be­gan analysing data in 2017 and iden­ti­fied trends that could lead to PMD fires with the aim of im­prov­ing the safety stan­dards and re­quire­ments for these de­vices.</p>
    <p>Pieces of ev­i­dence col­lected by in­ves­ti­ga­tors like Capt Han are bagged and sealed, be­fore be­ing sent to the Fire Foren­sics Lab­o­ra­tory at the SCDF head­quar­ters in Ubi. Pre­lim­i­nary ev­i­dence is val­i­dated and put through tests – for in­stance, to con­firm the pres­ence of flammable vapours.</p>

